A complementary space-based system, LISA, has been proposed for launch in 2020, but its funding is uncertain.
The two devices would operate in complementary frequency ranges (figure \figref{ligo-and-lisa-sensitivities}).
A selling point of LISA is that if it is launched, there are a number of sources in the sky, with known properties, that
are known to be easily within its range of sensitivity.\footnote{G. Nelemans, ``The Galactic Gravitational wave foreground,''
\url{arxiv.org/abs/0901.1778v1}} One excellent candidate is
HM Cancri, a pair of white dwarfs with an orbital period of 5.4 minutes, shorter than that of any 
other known binary star.\footnote{Roelofs et al., ``Spectroscopic Evidence for a 5.4-Minute Orbital Period in HM Cancri,''
\url{arxiv.org/abs/1003.0658v1}} 
