       in its previous position, delayed by the time it takes gravitational effects to propagate at $c$. At time $t$,
       the right-hand planet experiences the stronger deceleration corresponding to the left-hand planet's closer position at the earlier time $t'$,
       not its current position at $t$. Mechanical energy is not conserved, and the orbits will decay.}
  )
%>
\spacebetweenfigs
<%
  fig(
    'sticky-bead',
    %q{The sticky bead argument for the reality of gravitational waves. As a gravitational wave with the appropriate
            polarization passes by, the bead vibrates back and forth on the rod. Friction creates heat. This
